UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 2551
1 A RESOLUTION recognizing the 50th anniversary of the Scotia Mine Disaster in
2 Letcher County.
3 WHEREAS, on March 9, 1976, shortly after 11:30 a.m., an explosion occurred in
4 Mine No. 1 at the Scotia Coal Mining site at Black Mountain, Kentucky, killing 15
5 people; and
6 WHEREAS, two days later, as members of the community worked to rescue the
7 trapped miners, a second explosion occurred, claiming 11 more lives; and
8 WHEREAS, these two explosions combined resulted in one of the worst coal
9 mining disasters in United States History; and
10 WHEREAS, the 26 victims of these two explosions were beloved members of their
11 communities in eastern Kentucky, and their loss was felt across the region; and
12 WHEREAS, due to the instability of the conditions in the mines, the bodies of the
13 victims were unable to be recovered for several months, forcing families to mourn their
14 loved ones with empty caskets and resulting in protests to reopen the mines for body
15 recovery; and
16 WHEREAS, the lessons learned from these two explosions helped to reshape mine
17 safety regulations for years to come, as regulators and industry professionals came to
18 better understand how poorly ventilated air moves and can become trapped underground;
19 and
20 WHEREAS, the tragedy of the Scotia Mine explosions led to the Federal Mine
21 Safety and Health Act of 1977 and still informs regulations surrounding mine safety and
22 working conditions to this day; and
23 WHEREAS, because of the sacrifices of those miners and their families, miners
24 today work in much safer conditions, with extra precautions such as fireproof shelters,
25 emergency rations, and oxygen supplies; and
26 WHEREAS, while their loss remains an unforgettable tragedy, their legacy left on
27 the mining industry remains, saving hundreds if not thousands of lives over the last 50
Page 1 of 2
